To understand the fluorescence sensing ability of the prepared C-CDs, we measured their PL emission spectra using DA in different concentrations (0–30 µM) (
Fig. S5
). However, fluctuations in the PL intensity were observed, which suggest their poor sensing performance. The lack of special recognition moieties in the C-CDs towards DA sensing might be reasonable. Interestingly, the possible fluorescence quenching of B-CDs was observed using a myriad of DA concentrations (0–30 µM) as shown in Fig. 5
a. The linear regression plot was drawn between (F0-F)/F0) and DA concentrations (0–80 nM) with a good correlation coefficient of R2 = 0.9976 ( Fig. 5 b). Where, F0 and F represent the PL intensity of B-CDs without and with the addition of DA, respectively. The B-CDs have delivered a lower detection limit against DA around 4.25 nM, which was calculated using the equation 3σ/k. The σ and k denote the standard deviation and slope of the regression plot, respectively [63]. The obtained sensitivity is compatible with the threshold limit (10 nM to 1 µM) for DA levels in the human brain [64]. We again plotted the linear regression curves between (F0-F)/F0) and remaining DA concentrations (160, 320, and 640 nM, and 1, 2.5, 5.0, 7.5, 10, 12.5, 15, 20, 25, and 30 µM) to confirm the obtained lowest sensitivity of the B-CDs (
Fig. S6
). The R2 values for these concentrations were found to be low around 0.9658 and 0.9590, respectively. Table 1 summarizes and compares the sensitivity parameters for the proposed fluorescent sensor against recently developed analytical sensors [39,40,65–71]. For instance, the sensitivity of previously synthesized CDs was responsive only in the micromolar concentrations of DA. In contrast, the proposed B-CDs were highly sensitive, when investigated in nanomolar concentrations of DA. In addition, the plausible low detection limit (4.25 nM) was observed for the proposed B-CDs against DA detection when compared to the above-mentioned fluorescent sensors. Moreover, the selective recognition between the boronic acid and catechol groups is superior to the interaction between iron (Fe3+) ions and catechol groups of DA. For this reason, the proposed boronic acid-functionalized CDs (B-CDs) show high sensitivity and selectivity towards DA, when compared to the earlier reported iron-based carbon quantum dots (Fe-CQDs). Previously, researchers prepared various Fe-CQDs for DA detection using divergent precursors such as ferric nitrate, branched polyethylenimine (BPEI), and hemin, which are toxic to the central nervous system (CNS). In contrast to previous fluorescent sensors, B-CDs offer superior biocompatibility, ease of preparation, affordability, and non-enzymatic operation.
